<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910709-0032</DOCNO><DOCID>910709-0032.</DOCID><HL>   Thrift Purchases Weighed</HL><DATE>07/09/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   BAC TLMN</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)ILLINOIS (IL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   SAN FRANCISCO -- BankAmerica Corp. is looking intoacquiring several thrifts in Illinois, including Talman HomeFederal Savings andamp; Loan Association, Chicago's largest, inwhat would be the first step in a Midwest expansion drive.   BankAmerica officials have taken a look at Talman's booksbut, according to a BankAmerica official, there has been &quot;nomajor due-diligence&quot; report yet. The nation's second-largestbank is attracted by Talman Home's 45 branches, which arelocated primarily in the Chicago area.</LP><TEXT>   Talman, with assets of $5.8 billion, is under pressurefrom regulators to find new capital or a buyer because of itsweak financial condition. As of March 31, its cushion againstlosses, known as tangible capital, stood at almost $250million below regulatory requirements. Talman is a socalledphoenix institution that was formed by merging a group offailed thrifts under the supervision of federal regulators.It went public in 1986.   Talman Home officials couldn't be reached for comment.   For the past year, BankAmerica has been preoccupied withexpansion. It has purchased thrifts in several Western statesand recently has been an active bidder for failed thrifts inTexas. In April, it bid on the failed Bank of New EnglandCorp.</TEXT></DOC>